1. DEFINITIONS

1.1 "License" means the terms and conditions for use, copy, modification,
preparation of derivative work, reproduction, and distribution of Software.

1.2 "Licensor" means the copyright and/or patent owner or entity authorized by
the copyright and/or patent owner granting the License.

1.3 "Licensee" means the individual or entity exercising permissions granted by
this License.

1.4 "Software" means any copyrighted work, including software code, authored by
Licensor and made available under this License.

1.5 "Supply Chain" means the sequence of processes involved in the production
and/or distribution of a commodity, good, or service offered by the Licensee.

1.6 "Supply Chain Impacted Party" or "Supply Chain Impacted Parties" means any
person(s) directly impacted by any of Licensee's Supply Chain, including the
practices of all persons or entities within the Supply Chain.

1.7 "Duty of Care" is defined by its use in tort law, delict law, and/or
similar bodies of law, including a requirement to act with watchfulness,
attention, caution, and prudence toward any Supply Chain Impacted Party.

1.8 "Worker" includes permanent, temporary, and agency workers, as well as
piece-rate, salaried, hourly paid, young (minors), part-time, night, and
migrant workers.


2. INTELLECTUAL PROPERTY GRANTS

2.1 Grant of Copyright License: Licensor grants Licensee a worldwide,
non-exclusive, no-charge, royalty-free copyright license to use, copy, modify,
prepare derivative work, reproduce, or distribute the Software.

2.2 Grant of Patent License: Licensor grants Licensee a worldwide,
non-exclusive, no-charge, royalty-free patent license to make, have made, use,
offer to sell, sell, import, and otherwise transfer Software.


3. ETHICAL STANDARDS

Rights granted are expressly subject to Licensee's ongoing compliance with the
following conditions:

3.1 The Licensee SHALL NOT, whether directly or indirectly, through agents or
assigns:

3.1.1 Infringe upon any person's right to life or security of person, engage
in extrajudicial killings, or commit murder, without lawful cause (United
Nations Universal Declaration of Human Rights Article 3; International Covenant
on Civil and Political Rights Article 6).

3.1.2 Hold any person in slavery, servitude, or forced labor (United Nations
Universal Declaration of Human Rights Article 4; International Covenant on
Civil and Political Rights Article 8).

3.1.3 Contribute to the institution of slavery, slave trading, forced labor, or
unlawful child labor (United Nations Universal Declaration of Human Rights
Article 4; International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights Article 8).

3.1.4 Torture or subject any person to cruel, inhumane, or degrading treatment
or punishment (United Nations Universal Declaration of Human Rights Article 5;
International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights Article 7).

3.1.5 Discriminate on the basis of sex, gender, sexual orientation, race,
ethnicity, nationality, religion, caste, age, medical disability or impairment,
and/or any other like circumstances (United Nations Universal Declaration of
Human Rights Article 7; International Covenant on Economic, Social and Cultural
Rights Article 2; International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights Article
26).

3.1.6 Prevent any person from exercising their right to seek an effective
remedy by a competent court or national tribunal for actions violating
fundamental rights granted to them by applicable constitutions, applicable laws,
or by this License (United Nations Universal Declaration of Human Rights
Article 8; International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights Articles 9 and
14).

3.1.7 Subject any person to arbitrary arrest, detention, or exile (United
Nations Universal Declaration of Human Rights Article 9; International Covenant
on Civil and Political Rights Article 9).

3.1.8 Subject any person to arbitrary interference with privacy, family, home,
or correspondence without express written consent of the person (United Nations
Universal Declaration of Human Rights Article 12; International Covenant on
Civil and Political Rights Article 17).

3.1.9 Arbitrarily deprive any person of their property (United Nations
Universal Declaration of Human Rights Article 17).

3.1.10 Forcibly remove indigenous peoples from their lands or territories or
take any action with the aim or effect of dispossessing indigenous peoples from
their lands, territories, or resources, including intellectual property or
traditional knowledge of indigenous peoples, without free, prior, and informed
consent of indigenous peoples concerned (United Nations Declaration on the
Rights of Indigenous Peoples Articles 8 and 10).

3.1.11 Be an individual or entity, or a representative, agent, affiliate,
successor, attorney, or assign of an individual or entity, on the FFI Solutions
Carbon Underground 200 list.

3.1.12 Commit ecocide: the unlawful or wanton acts committed with knowledge
that there is a substantial likelihood of severe and either widespread or
long-term damage to the environment being caused by those acts.

3.1.13 Be an individual or entity, or a representative, agent, affiliate,
successor, attorney, or assign of an individual or entity, that engages in
fossil fuel or mineral exploration, extraction, development, or sale.

3.1.14 Be an individual or entity, or a representative, agent, affiliate,
successor, attorney, or assign of an individual or entity, identified by the
Boycott, Divestment, Sanctions (BDS) movement on its website as a target for
boycott.

3.1.15 Be an individual or entity that engages in any commercial transactions
with the Taliban or is a representative, agent, affiliate, successor, attorney,
or assign of the Taliban.

3.1.16 Be an individual or entity that engages in any commercial transactions
with the Myanmar/Burmese government or is a representative, agent, affiliate,
successor, attorney, or assign of the Myanmar/Burmese government.

3.1.17 Be an individual or entity, or a representative, agent, affiliate,
successor, attorney, or assign of any individual or entity, that does business
in, purchases goods from, or otherwise benefits from goods produced in the
Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region of China.

3.1.18 Be an individual or entity which U.S. Customs and Border Protection (CBP)
has currently issued a Withhold Release Order (WRO) or finding against, or that
is a representative, agent, affiliate, successor, attorney, or assign of an
individual or entity that does business with an individual or entity which
currently has a WRO or finding from CBP issued against it.

3.1.19 Be an individual or entity, or a representative, agent, affiliate,
successor, attorney, or assign of an individual or entity, that is mentioned in
a truth commission report of any country that has undergone a formal or informal
transitional justice process and that did not adequately remedy the communities
impacted by it or did not follow the recommendations of the truth commission or
any other transitional justice mechanism.

3.1.20 Be an individual or entity, or a representative, agent, affiliate,
successor, attorney, or assign of an individual or entity, responsible for the
detention of immigrants, refugees, or asylum seekers, irrespective of past,
present, or pending legal status.

3.1.21 Be a government agency or multinational corporation, or a representative,
agent, affiliate, successor, attorney, or assign of a government or multinational
corporation, which participates in mass surveillance programs.

3.1.22 Be an entity or a representative, agent, affiliate, successor, attorney,
or assign of an entity which conducts military activities.

3.1.23 Be an individual or entity, or a representative, agent, affiliate,
successor, attorney, or assign of an individual or entity, that provides goods
or services to, or otherwise enters into any commercial contracts with, any
local, state, or federal law enforcement agency.

3.1.24 Be an individual or entity, or a representative, agent, affiliate,
successor, attorney, or assign of an individual or entity, that broadcasts
messages promoting killing, torture, or other forms of extreme violence.

3.1.25 Interfere with Workers' free exercise of the right to organize and
associate (United Nations Universal Declaration of Human Rights Article 20; ILO
Convention 87; International Covenant on Economic, Social and Cultural Rights
Article 8).

3.1.26 Harm the environment in a manner inconsistent with local, state,
national, or international law.

3.2 The Licensee SHALL:

3.2.1 Always use worker driven social responsibility mechanisms over traditional
social auditing mechanisms, to the extent the Licensee uses any social auditing
mechanisms at all.

3.2.2 Provide clear, accessible supply chain data to the public, including all
data on Licensee's website or other online platform accessible to the public via
an internet search on a common internet search engine, which will include, where
applicable, manufacturers, top tier suppliers, subcontractors, cooperatives,
component parts producers, and farms.

3.2.3 Provide equal pay for equal work where performance of such work requires
equal skill, effort, and responsibility, and which are performed under similar
working conditions, except where such payment is made pursuant to:
(a) a seniority system
(b) a merit system
(c) a system which measures earnings by quantity or quality of production
(d) a differential based on any factor other than sex, gender, sexual
    orientation, race, ethnicity, nationality, religion, caste, age, medical
    disability or impairment, and/or any other like circumstances
(United Nations Universal Declaration of Human Rights Article 23; International
Covenant on Economic, Social and Cultural Rights Articles 6, 7, and 10;
International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights Article 26).

3.2.4 Allow for reasonable limitation of working hours and periodic holidays
with pay (United Nations Universal Declaration of Human Rights Article 24;
International Covenant on Economic, Social and Cultural Rights Article 7).


4. SUPPLY CHAIN IMPACTED PARTIES

4.1 Licensee voluntarily accepts a Duty of Care for Supply Chain Impacted
Parties of this License, including individuals and communities impacted by
violations of the Ethical Standards. The Duty of Care is breached when a
provision within the Ethical Standards section is violated by a Licensee, one of
its successors or assigns, or by an individual or entity that exists within the
Supply Chain prior to a good or service reaching the Licensee.

4.2 Breaches of the Duty of Care create a private right of action, allowing any
Supply Chain Impacted Party harmed by the Licensee to take legal action against
the Licensee in accordance with applicable negligence laws, regardless if
Licensee is directly responsible for the harms suffered by a Supply Chain
Impacted Party. Nothing in this section shall be interpreted to include acts
committed by individuals outside the scope of their employment.


